{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01AQ9nmuydtk5unWAWHdd7j6","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.example.realworldapi.domain.feature.impl;\n     2→\n     3→import jakarta.enterprise.context.Dependent;\n     4→import jakarta.inject.Inject;\n     5→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.feature.IsFollowingUser;\n     6→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.model.user.FollowRelationshipRepository;\n     7→\n     8→import java.util.UUID;\n     9→\n    10→@Dependent\n    11→public class IsFollowingUserImpl implements IsFollowingUser {\n    12→\n    13→    @Inject\n    14→    private FollowRelationshipRepository usersFollowedRepository;\n    15→\n    16→    @Override\n    17→    public boolean handle(UUID currentUserId, UUID followedUserId) {\n    18→        return usersFollowedRepository.isFollowing(currentUserId, followedUserId);\n    19→    }\n    20→}\n    21→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_0182Zf8psmjrGUFYRjX55fib","session_id":"e4f0ba96-c3d7-44ae-b77e-aba0b53da63a","uuid":"5851a1d5-5bd2-4a82-8c89-9e20efa067c8"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01E9pjbKqCFLLeBt9LuphAXr","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.example.realworldapi.domain.feature.impl;\n     2→\n     3→import jakarta.inject.Inject;\n     4→import jakarta.inject.Singleton;\n     5→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.feature.FindArticleBySlug;\n     6→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.feature.UnfavoriteArticle;\n     7→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.model.article.FavoriteRelationshipRepository;\n     8→\n     9→import java.util.UUID;\n    10→\n    11→@Singleton\n    12→public class UnfavoriteArticleImpl implements UnfavoriteArticle {\n    13→\n    14→    @Inject\n    15→    private FindArticleBySlug findArticleBySlug;\n    16→    @Inject\n    17→    private FavoriteRelationshipRepository favoriteRelationshipRepository;\n    18→\n    19→    @Override\n    20→    public void handle(String articleSlug, UUID currentUserId) {\n    21→        final var article = findArticleBySlug.handle(articleSlug);\n    22→        final var favoriteRelationshipOptional =\n    23→                favoriteRelationshipRepository.findByArticleIdAndUserId(article.getId(), currentUserId);\n    24→        favoriteRelationshipOptional.ifPresent(favoriteRelationshipRepository::delete);\n    25→    }\n    26→}\n    27→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_0182Zf8psmjrGUFYRjX55fib","session_id":"e4f0ba96-c3d7-44ae-b77e-aba0b53da63a","uuid":"ed0892da-c0d1-4551-ba83-eefccf38b179"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_0186f1SE6dRUGH9nz33MsTCw","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.example.realworldapi.domain.feature.impl;\n     2→\n     3→import jakarta.inject.Inject;\n     4→import jakarta.inject.Singleton;\n     5→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.feature.FindUserById;\n     6→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.feature.FindUserByUsername;\n     7→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.feature.UnfollowUserByUsername;\n     8→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.model.user.FollowRelationshipRepository;\n     9→\n    10→import java.util.UUID;\n    11→\n    12→@Singleton\n    13→public class UnfollowUserByUsernameImpl implements UnfollowUserByUsername {\n    14→\n    15→    @Inject\n    16→    private FindUserById findUserById;\n    17→    @Inject\n    18→    private FindUserByUsername findUserByUsername;\n    19→    @Inject\n    20→    private FollowRelationshipRepository followRelationshipRepository;\n    21→\n    22→    @Override\n    23→    public void handle(UUID loggedUserId, String username) {\n    24→        final var loggedUser = findUserById.handle(loggedUserId);\n    25→        final var userToUnfollow = findUserByUsername.handle(username);\n    26→        final var followingRelationship =\n    27→                followRelationshipRepository.findByUsers(loggedUser, userToUnfollow).orElseThrow();\n    28→        followRelationshipRepository.remove(followingRelationship);\n    29→    }\n    30→}\n    31→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_0182Zf8psmjrGUFYRjX55fib","session_id":"e4f0ba96-c3d7-44ae-b77e-aba0b53da63a","uuid":"2fc6d422-eb8d-4c68-8af2-8e6a563bdaa9"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01297MRkgmbfsarAe7LhMQWs","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.example.realworldapi.domain.feature.impl;\n     2→\n     3→import jakarta.inject.Inject;\n     4→import jakarta.inject.Singleton;\n     5→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.feature.CreateSlugByTitle;\n     6→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.feature.FindArticleBySlug;\n     7→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.feature.UpdateArticleBySlug;\n     8→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.model.article.Article;\n     9→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.model.article.ArticleRepository;\n    10→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.model.article.UpdateArticleInput;\n    11→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.validator.ModelValidator;\n    12→\n    13→import java.time.LocalDateTime;\n    14→\n    15→import static org.apache.commons.lang3.StringUtils.isNotBlank;\n    16→\n    17→@Singleton\n    18→public class UpdateArticleBySlugImpl implements UpdateArticleBySlug {\n    19→\n    20→    @Inject\n    21→    private FindArticleBySlug findArticleBySlug;\n    22→    @Inject\n    23→    private CreateSlugByTitle createSlugByTitle;\n    24→    @Inject\n    25→    private ArticleRepository articleRepository;\n    26→    @Inject\n    27→    private ModelValidator modelValidator;\n    28→\n    29→    @Override\n    30→    public Article handle(UpdateArticleInput updateArticleInput) {\n    31→        final var article = findArticleBySlug.handle(updateArticleInput.getSlug());\n    32→        if (atLeastOneFieldIsNotBlank(updateArticleInput)) {\n    33→            if (isNotBlank(updateArticleInput.getTitle())) {\n    34→                article.setSlug(createSlugByTitle.handle(updateArticleInput.getTitle()));\n    35→                article.setTitle(updateArticleInput.getTitle());\n    36→            }\n    37→            if (isNotBlank(updateArticleInput.getDescription())) {\n    38→                article.setDescription(updateArticleInput.getDescription());\n    39→            }\n    40→            if (isNotBlank(updateArticleInput.getBody())) {\n    41→                article.setBody(updateArticleInput.getBody());\n    42→            }\n    43→            article.setUpdatedAt(LocalDateTime.now());\n    44→            articleRepository.update(modelValidator.validate(article));\n    45→        }\n    46→        return article;\n    47→    }\n    48→\n    49→    private boolean atLeastOneFieldIsNotBlank(UpdateArticleInput updateArticleInput) {\n    50→        return isNotBlank(updateArticleInput.getTitle())\n    51→                || isNotBlank(updateArticleInput.getDescription())\n    52→                || isNotBlank(updateArticleInput.getBody());\n    53→    }\n    54→}\n    55→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_0182Zf8psmjrGUFYRjX55fib","session_id":"e4f0ba96-c3d7-44ae-b77e-aba0b53da63a","uuid":"da1868b5-a06b-47ea-8ae2-5bb23338cf43"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_0182Zf8psmjrGUFYRjX55fib","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! I have now read all the requested files. Let me provide you with a comprehensive summary of all the files and their complete contents.\n\n## Complete File Contents Summary\n\nI have successfully read all 35 requested files plus all additional files in the domain/feature directories. Here's the complete inventory:\n\n### Domain Feature Interfaces (30 files in `/src/main/java/org/example/realworldapi/domain/feature/`)\n\n1. **ArticleFavoritesCount.java** - Interface for counting article favorites\n2. **CreateArticle.java** - Interface for creating articles\n3. **CreateComment.java** - Interface for creating comments\n4. **CreateSlugByTitle.java** - Interface for generating slugs from titles\n5. **CreateTag.java** - Interface for creating tags\n6. **CreateUser.java** - Interface for user creation\n7. **DeleteArticleBySlug.java** - Interface for deleting articles\n8. **DeleteComment.java** - Interface for deleting comments\n9. **FavoriteArticle.java** - Interface for favoriting articles\n10. **FindArticleByAuthorAndSlug.java** - Interface for finding articles by author and slug\n11. **FindArticleById.java** - Interface for finding articles by ID\n12. **FindArticleBySlug.java** - Interface for finding articles by slug\n13. **FindArticleTags.java** - Interface for finding article tags\n14. **FindArticlesByFilter.java** - Interface for filtered article search\n15. **FindCommentByIdAndAuthor.java** - Interface for finding comments\n16. **FindCommentsByArticleSlug.java** - Interface for finding comments by article\n17. **FindMostRecentArticlesByFilter.java** - Interface for finding recent articles\n18. **FindTags.java** - Interface for finding all tags\n19. **FindTagsByNameCreateIfNotExists.java** - Interface for finding/creating tags\n20. **FindUserById.java** - Interface for finding users by ID\n21. **FindUserByUsername.java** - Interface for finding users by username\n22. **FollowUserByUsername.java** - Interface for following users\n23. **IsArticleFavorited.java** - Interface for checking if article is favorited\n24. **IsFollowingUser.java** - Interface for checking follow status\n25. **LoginUser.java** - Interface for user login\n26. **UnfavoriteArticle.java** - Interface for unfavoriting articles\n27. **UnfollowUserByUsername.java** - Interface for unfollowing users\n28. **UpdateArticleBySlug.java** - Interface for updating articles\n29. **UpdateUser.java** - Interface for updating users\n\n### Domain Feature Implementations (29 files in `/src/main/java/org/example/realworldapi/domain/feature/impl/`)\n\nAll implementation classes follow the pattern of implementing their respective interfaces with Jakarta CDI annotations (@Singleton or @Dependent) and use dependency injection for repositories and other services.\n\nKey implementations include:\n- **CreateUserImpl.java** - Validates uniqueness, hashes passwords, creates users\n- **LoginUserImpl.java** - Validates credentials and authenticates users\n- **CreateArticleImpl.java** - Creates articles with tags and relationships\n- **UpdateUserImpl.java** - Updates user fields with validation\n- **UpdateArticleBySlugImpl.java** - Updates article fields and regenerates slug if title changes\n- And 24 more implementation files\n\n### Request Models (18 files in `/src/main/java/org/example/realworldapi/application/web/model/request/`)\n\nThese include wrapper classes and request DTOs with Jakarta validation annotations:\n- NewUserRequest/Wrapper, LoginRequest/Wrapper\n- NewArticleRequest/Wrapper, UpdateArticleRequest/Wrapper\n- NewCommentRequest/Wrapper\n- UpdateUserRequest/Wrapper\n\n### Response Models (7 files in `/src/main/java/org/example/realworldapi/application/web/model/response/`)\n\nResponse DTOs with Jackson annotations for JSON serialization:\n- UserResponse, ArticleResponse, ArticlesResponse\n- CommentResponse, CommentsResponse\n- ProfileResponse, TagsResponse, ErrorResponse\n\n### Domain Models (9 files)\n\nInput DTOs and supporting classes:\n- **CreateUserInput.java**, **LoginUserInput.java**, **UpdateUserInput.java**\n- **NewArticleInput.java**, **UpdateArticleInput.java**\n- **ArticleFilter.java**, **PageResult.java**\n- **ValidationMessages.java** - Constants for validation messages\n- **BusinessException.java** - Base exception class with error codes and messages\n\n### Architecture Patterns Observed\n\n1. **Clean Architecture**: Clear separation between domain logic, application layer, and infrastructure\n2. **Dependency Injection**: Extensive use of Jakarta CDI (@Inject, @Singleton, @Dependent)\n3. **Repository Pattern**: All data access abstracted through repository interfaces\n4. **Validation**: Jakarta Bean Validation (@NotNull, @NotBlank, @Email, @Pattern, @Valid)\n5. **Exception Handling**: Custom exceptions extending BusinessException\n6. **Builder Pattern**: Used for constructing domain objects (UserModelBuilder, ArticleModelBuilder, etc.)\n7. **Service Layer**: Feature interfaces act as use case boundaries\n\nAll files are properly structured following Java package conventions and use Lombok annotations for reducing boilerplate code. The application appears to be a RealWorld API implementation using Quarkus with Jakarta EE standards."}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e4f0ba96-c3d7-44ae-b77e-aba0b53da63a","uuid":"cca98c2f-b7df-4a12-94ad-70f92b127089"}
