{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_018rwdGNnYUgGQEc16dw2b1o","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.example.realworldapi.application.web;\n     2→\n     3→import jakarta.ws.rs.ApplicationPath;\n     4→import jakarta.ws.rs.core.Application;\n     5→\n     6→@ApplicationPath(\"api\")\n     7→public class App extends Application {\n     8→}\n     9→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01XybQwgJDvZQABSCtv133UN","session_id":"e4f0ba96-c3d7-44ae-b77e-aba0b53da63a","uuid":"ba6c357d-78de-4aac-a4c8-82a876009ae4"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01XybQwgJDvZQABSCtv133UN","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Summary of findings:\n\n1. Files containing \"AtLeastOneFieldMustBeNotNull\":\n   - /src/main/java/org/example/realworldapi/infrastructure/web/validation/constraint/AtLeastOneFieldMustBeNotNull.java \n     - A custom validation annotation to ensure at least one field is not null\n   - /src/main/java/org/example/realworldapi/infrastructure/web/validation/validator/AtLeastOneFieldMustBeNotNullValidator.java\n     - A validator that implements the custom constraint, using reflection to check field values\n\n2. Infrastructure/web/validation files:\n   - Exactly the same files found in the first search, which I've already detailed above\n\n3. Application.properties:\n   - Located at /src/main/resources/application.properties\n   - Highlights:\n     - Quarkus configuration for a RealWorld API\n     - HTTP port set to 8080\n     - PostgreSQL database configuration\n     - JWT configuration with a secret and 10-minute expiration\n     - CORS enabled with permissive settings\n\n4. JAX-RS Application class:\n   - /src/main/java/org/example/realworldapi/application/web/App.java\n   - A simple JAX-RS Application class \n   - Uses @ApplicationPath(\"api\") \n   - Extends jakarta.ws.rs.core.Application\n   - Sets the base path for the API to \"/api\"\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these files or findings?"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e4f0ba96-c3d7-44ae-b77e-aba0b53da63a","uuid":"0a88d8ae-2bd7-4911-be81-09c70d7b6e31"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01CrvGEznet6wncLQBSDhDYt","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have the full picture. Here's my analysis of the HTTP 400 issue:\n\n**Root Cause**: The Quarkus REST (RESTEasy Reactive or Classic) uses its own ObjectMapper for deserializing request bodies. In Quarkus, when there are multiple `ObjectMapper` CDI beans, the framework uses the **default unqualified** one managed by Quarkus itself (configured via `ObjectMapperCustomizer`). The issue is that the `@Named(\"wrappingObjectMapper\")` producer in `SerializerConfig` might still be picked up as an ambiguous unqualified bean by Quarkus REST, OR there could be a validation issue.\n\nActually, looking more carefully - the wrapper classes like `NewUserRequestWrapper` have a `user` field. The JSON `{\"user\": {...}}` should map directly to `NewUserRequestWrapper.user`. This should work fine with Quarkus's default ObjectMapper. The 400 error could be caused by:\n\n1. Bean validation failing (the `@NotNull` on `NewUserRequest` class itself, not the field)\n2. Or the Quarkus REST Jackson provider picking up the wrapping ObjectMapper (with `UNWRAP_ROOT_VALUE` enabled), which would try to unwrap the root, causing `{\"user\":{...}}` to look for a second level of wrapping\n\nThe most likely culprit is option 2. If Quarkus REST somehow picks up the `@Named(\"wrappingObjectMapper\")` bean for deserialization, it would try to unwrap `{\"user\":{...}}` and fail because `NewUserRequestWrapper` doesn't have `@JsonRootName`.\n\nLet me fix the approach: I need to make sure the wrapping ObjectMapper is NOT available as the default CDI ObjectMapper. I should also check that `start.sh` doesn't kill the container on test failure for debugging.\n\nLet me also check the `@Secured` annotation and filter setup since that also affects how requests are processed:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":604,"cache_read_input_tokens":50827,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":604,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":792},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e4f0ba96-c3d7-44ae-b77e-aba0b53da63a","uuid":"fe0eac00-c0b3-485b-a6bb-faa56f3c5767"}
